# Cursor Rules: Error Handling & Exception Management

rules:
  - id: error_handling.exception_hierarchy
    description: |
      All exceptions must use the established Mavaia exception hierarchy.
      - Base all custom exceptions on `MavaiaError` or its subclasses
      - Use `ModuleError` for module-related errors
      - Use `APIError` for API-related errors
      - Use `ClientError` for client-related errors
      - Use `RegistryError` for registry-related errors
      - Create specific exception classes for distinct error types
      - Never raise generic `Exception` or `RuntimeError` without context
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.exception_context
    description: |
      All exceptions must include meaningful context for debugging.
      - Use the `context` parameter in MavaiaError to include debugging information
      - Include relevant identifiers (module_name, operation, parameter names)
      - Include error causes and reasons
      - Do not include sensitive information (API keys, passwords, PII) in context
      - Context should be sufficient to diagnose the issue without code inspection
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.exception_messages
    description: |
      Exception messages must be clear, actionable, and user-friendly.
      - Write messages that explain what went wrong and why
      - Include actionable guidance when possible
      - Use consistent message formatting across similar exceptions
      - Avoid technical jargon in user-facing error messages
      - Include relevant values in messages (parameter names, expected types)
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.module_errors
    description: |
      Module errors must follow established patterns.
      - Use `ModuleNotFoundError` when a module cannot be found
      - Use `ModuleInitializationError` when module initialization fails
      - Use `ModuleOperationError` when a module operation fails
      - Include module name, operation name, and reason in all module errors
      - Provide context about what was attempted and why it failed
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.api_errors
    description: |
      API errors must be properly mapped to HTTP responses.
      - Use `AuthenticationError` for authentication failures (maps to 401)
      - Use `ValidationError` for request validation failures (maps to 400)
      - Include field name and reason in validation errors
      - Use appropriate HTTP status codes in API error responses
      - Never expose internal implementation details in API error messages
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.parameter_validation
    description: |
      Parameter validation errors must be raised with clear information.
      - Use `InvalidParameterError` for invalid parameter values
      - Include parameter name, value (if safe), and reason for invalidity
      - Validate parameters early, before expensive operations
      - Provide specific validation error messages
      - Use Pydantic validation for API request validation
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.error_propagation
    description: |
      Errors must be propagated appropriately through the call stack.
      - Let exceptions propagate unless you can handle them meaningfully
      - Catch specific exception types, not generic Exception
      - Re-raise exceptions with additional context when appropriate
      - Use exception chaining (`raise ... from ...`) to preserve original exceptions
      - Log errors before re-raising when appropriate
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.error_recovery
    description: |
      Error recovery strategies must be explicit and documented.
      - Only catch exceptions when you can handle them meaningfully
      - Document recovery strategies in code comments
      - Use fallbacks only when they represent correct architectural solutions
      - Never silently swallow exceptions without logging
      - Implement retry logic with exponential backoff for transient errors
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.logging_errors
    description: |
      Errors must be logged with appropriate context before handling.
      - Log errors at appropriate log levels (ERROR for failures, WARNING for recoverable issues)
      - Include full exception context in logs (use `exc_info=True` in logging)
      - Log errors before re-raising or returning error responses
      - Include request/operation context in error logs
      - Do not log sensitive information (API keys, passwords, PII)
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.user_facing_errors
    description: |
      User-facing error messages must be appropriate for the audience.
      - API errors should be user-friendly and actionable
      - Internal errors should include technical details for debugging
      - Never expose stack traces or internal implementation details to users
      - Provide error codes for programmatic error handling
      - Include suggestions for resolving errors when possible
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.error_safety
    description: |
      Error handling must not introduce security vulnerabilities.
      - Never expose sensitive information in error messages
      - Sanitize error messages before returning to users
      - Use error codes instead of detailed messages for sensitive operations
      - Log detailed errors internally, return sanitized errors to users
      - Validate and sanitize all user inputs before processing
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.exception_safety
    description: |
      Code must maintain exception safety guarantees.
      - Ensure resources are cleaned up even when exceptions occur (use try/finally or context managers)
      - Do not leave system state inconsistent after exceptions
      - Use context managers for resource management
      - Implement proper cleanup in exception handlers
      - Document exception safety guarantees in docstrings
    severity: error

  - id: error_handling.error_testing
    description: |
      Error conditions must be explicitly tested.
      - Test all exception types raised by code
      - Test error messages for clarity and correctness
      - Test error context and metadata
      - Test error recovery and fallback mechanisms
      - Use `pytest.raises()` for exception testing
    severity: error

examples:
  - description: "Proper exception usage with context"
    language: python
    code: |
      from oricli_core.exceptions import ModuleOperationError, InvalidParameterError
      
      
      def execute_operation(self, operation: str, params: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]:
          """Execute module operation with proper error handling"""
          # Validate operation
          if operation not in self.metadata.operations:
              raise ValueError(
                  f"Unknown operation: {operation}",
                  context={"module": self.metadata.name, "operation": operation}
              )
          
          # Validate parameters
          if "text" not in params:
              raise InvalidParameterError(
                  parameter="text",
                  value=None,
                  reason="Required parameter 'text' is missing"
              )
          
          # Execute operation
          try:
              result = self._perform_operation(operation, params)
              return result
          except Exception as e:
              # Re-raise with module context
              raise ModuleOperationError(
                  module_name=self.metadata.name,
                  operation=operation,
                  reason=str(e)
              ) from e

  - description: "Error handling with logging and recovery"
    language: python
    code: |
      import logging
      from oricli_core.exceptions import ModuleInitializationError
      
      logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
      
      
      def initialize_module(self) -> bool:
          """Initialize module with error handling and logging"""
          try:
              # Attempt initialization
              self._load_model()
              self._setup_resources()
              return True
          except FileNotFoundError as e:
              logger.error(
                  f"Model file not found for module {self.metadata.name}",
                  exc_info=True,
                  extra={"module": self.metadata.name, "error": str(e)}
              )
              raise ModuleInitializationError(
                  module_name=self.metadata.name,
                  reason=f"Model file not found: {e}"
              ) from e
          except Exception as e:
              logger.error(
                  f"Unexpected error initializing module {self.metadata.name}",
                  exc_info=True,
                  extra={"module": self.metadata.name, "error": str(e)}
              )
              raise ModuleInitializationError(
                  module_name=self.metadata.name,
                  reason=f"Unexpected error: {e}"
              ) from e

  - description: "Error handling with context managers"
    language: python
    code: |
      from contextlib import contextmanager
      from oricli_core.exceptions import ModuleOperationError
      
      
      @contextmanager
      def operation_context(module_name: str, operation: str):
          """Context manager for module operations with error handling"""
          try:
              yield
          except Exception as e:
              raise ModuleOperationError(
                  module_name=module_name,
                  operation=operation,
                  reason=str(e)
              ) from e
      
      
      def execute(self, operation: str, params: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]:
          """Execute with context manager for exception safety"""
          with operation_context(self.metadata.name, operation):
              return self._perform_operation(operation, params)

references:
  - Mavaia exception hierarchy: oricli_core/exceptions.py
  - Python exception handling: https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/errors.html
  - Exception safety: https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/exceptions
